How the logging is handled for bic console ?  how the logging is handled if we switch console b/w host and bic ?

For each server, a log file will be generated when BMC has booted, any data received from corresponding tty serial endpoint (e.g., ttyS0) will be logged into the file, when switching between host and bic, it only change the mux of the ttyS, so the log is mixed.
According to the suggestion from Michael, we divided the listening port of Host/BIC from 2200~2207 to 2200~2203/2300~2303, to provide more intuitive usage.

Can we switch this to be based on a machine feature (fb-compute-multihost?) instead of ":greatlakes"?  Do they all have a mux like this?  Is there something about BIC that we should add as a machine feature?

I'd prefer to not have very many ":greatlakes" specified directly in meta-facebook.  That is just asking for us to have tons of them as we support more systems.

Please relook at this whole file.

Hi Patrick,

The overall workflow of the SoL multi-host is that Systemd listens the port that the socket configured, launch the targeted service to switch the mux, then call the client of obmc-console. I agree with that meta-facebook should not appear project-specific statements, so I have two solutions for this:

1. Switch the sockets and the services to be fb-compute-multihost's feature, then put the select-uart-mux script into project-layer.

2. Put all of the files above into Greatlakes to maximum the flexibility.

The first solution assumes that fb-compute-multihost all have 4 slots, and each slot have a host and bic, and locks the listening port of the sockets, leave only the select-uart-mux for project-spcific implementation; The second one just leave everything into Greatlakes, just like the lastest patch set (20) I just uploaded.

Currently, in YV2, YV3, and YV3.5, it do follow the rule in solution 1, but I'm not sure that other platforms all follows it, so I'd prefer to solution 2.

If there is any questions or concerns, please let me know, thanks.
Let's go with (1) until we determine it doesn't work.  We want to avoid as much platform-specific code as possible.
Done.
